  "prompt": "What is the difference between fact and theory in science jargon?",
  "response": "In scientific terminology, the difference between a fact and a theory is significant and reflects varying levels of certainty and explanatory power.\n\n**Fact:** In science, a fact is an observation that has been repeatedly confirmed and for all practical purposes is accepted as \"true.\" Facts are simple, basic observations that are agreed upon by consensus. For example, it is a fact that water boils at 100\u00b0C under normal atmospheric pressure.\n\n**Theory:** A theory, on the other hand, is a well-substantiated explanation of some aspect of the natural world that incorporates facts, laws, inferences, and tested hypotheses. Theories are not just guesses; they are comprehensive frameworks that explain and predict phenomena based on evidence. For instance, the theory of evolution by natural selection is a theory that explains the diversity of life on Earth through mechanisms that have been extensively tested and validated.\n\n**Key Differences:**\n1. **Certainty and Complexity:**\n   - Facts are observations confirmed to such a degree that it would be perverse to withhold provisional assent.\n   - Theories are complex explanations that incorporate a wide array of facts and validated hypotheses.\n\n2. **Scope and Detail:**\n   - Facts are often simple and specific.\n   - Theories are broad and detailed, offering explanations that can unify various facts and observations.\n\n3. **Function in Science:**\n   - Facts provide the foundational data on which scientific knowledge is built.\n   - Theories provide the overarching frameworks that make sense of the data, guiding future research and understanding.\n\n4. **Evolution in Scientific Understanding:**\n   - Facts, while they may become more precise, do not change in their fundamental truth.\n   - Theories can evolve and be refined as new evidence is discovered, and they may be replaced by more accurate theories over time.\n\nUnderstanding these distinctions helps in appreciating the depth and rigor of scientific inquiry and communication.",
